1. Track Your Position
You currently have a world struct that holds pointers to maps, but you don't have a way to track where the player is.

Define two integer variables (e.g., current_x and current_y) in your main function.
Initialize them to the center of the array (200, 200).
These will serve as your internal coordinates. When you display coordinates to the user, you will calculate them relative to this center (e.g., display_x = current_x - 200).
2. The "Lazy Loading" Loop
Your main loop needs to change from just reading input to a "Check -> Generate -> Display" cycle.

Check: When the loop starts (or after movement), look at the world array at [current_y][current_x].
If it is NULL: This map hasn't been visited yet. You need to malloc a new map struct and assign it to that pointer. Then, call your generation functions to fill it with data.
If it is NOT NULL: The map already exists. Do not generate it again. Just print the map pointed to by that slot.
3. Refactoring generate_roads (The Gate Logic)
This is the most complex part of this assignment. Currently, your generate_roads function picks random locations for all four gates. This needs to change.

Pass Arguments: Change the function signature to accept four integers representing the required gate locations for North, South, East, and West.
Sentinel Values: Decide on a value (like -1) that means "I don't care, pick a random one."
Neighbor Checking: Before calling generate_roads for a new map at (x, y), look at the neighbors in the world array:
North Neighbor (y - 1): If it exists (is not NULL), look at its South gate. Pass that value as the North gate requirement for your new map.
South Neighbor (y + 1): If it exists, its North gate dictates your new South gate.
East/West: Same logic.
No Neighbor: If the neighbor is NULL, pass your sentinel value (-1) so the generator picks a random gate.
World Borders: If current_y is 0 (top edge of the world), you must force the North gate to be "closed" (you might need a specific value or flag for this).
4. Refactoring generate_builds (The Probability Logic)
Currently, your building generator places buildings randomly or based on hardcoded logic.

Manhattan Distance: In main, calculate the distance from the center: abs(current_x - 200) + abs(current_y - 200).
Pass Distance: Update generate_builds to accept this distance as a parameter.
Apply Formula: Inside the function, use the formula provided in the PDF to calculate the percentage chance (0-100%) of a building spawning.
Dice Roll: Generate a random number (0-100). If it's lower than the calculated chance, place the building. If not, skip it.
Safety: Ensure the center map (distance 0) always spawns both buildings.
5. Handling Input
Update your input parsing to handle the new commands:

n, s, e, w: Update current_y or current_x accordingly. Check if the new coordinate is within bounds (0-400). If it is, the loop repeats and handles the "Check -> Generate -> Display" logic for the new coordinate.
f x y: Read two integers. Convert them from relative coordinates (e.g., -5, 5) to internal coordinates (195, 205). Update your current position variables.
q: Break the loop.
Summary of Workflow
User enters 'n'.
Decrement current_y.
Check world.m[current_y][current_x].
It's NULL? Allocate memory.
Check world.m[current_y + 1][current_x] (the map we just came from). It exists!
Read its North gate.
Call generate_roads, forcing the South gate to match, and randomizing the others.
Call generate_builds with the new distance.
Print the map.